│ functions `collectFromPHI` and `collectFromBlock` are calling each other in a loop, which eventually leads to a stack overflow.                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The core of the problem is that `collectFromPHI` iterates through the incoming blocks specified in the PHI node's operands. For the invalid IR, this includes the unreachable block      │
│ `bb`. `collectFromPHI` then calls `collectFromBlock` for this block `bb`. Since `bb` is unreachable, it has no predecessors. The logic in `collectFromBlock` seems to handle this by     │
│ trying to find guards on the path from the entry of the function to `bb`. However, because of the invalid CFG, the analysis gets stuck in a recursive loop.                              │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The block `bb` is unreachable, so it should not be considered as a predecessor for `header`. The PHI node is malformed. While LLVM's verifier should catch this, analyses should ideally │
│ be robust against such cases to prevent crashes.                                                                                                                                         │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ A simple fix is to ensure that when `collectFromPHI` processes incoming blocks, it only considers blocks that are actual predecessors of the PHI's parent block. This can be done by     │
│ checking if the incoming block from the PHI operand is in the set of predecessors for the PHI's block.                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The relevant code is in `llvm/lib/Analysis/ScalarEvolution.cpp`, inside the `LoopGuards::collectFromPHI` function. I will add a check to see if `PN.getIncomingBlock(i)` is a            │
│ predecessor of `PN.getParent()`. If not, I will skip it. This will prevent the analysis from going down a path that doesn't exist in the CFG, thus breaking the infinite recursion.      │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ I will use `is_contained` to check for predecessor validity. This requires including `llvm/ADT/STLExtras.h`.                                                                             │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
